<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<backmatter xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="meta-back">
  <title>Back Matter</title>

  <appendix xml:id="back-acknowledgements">
    <title>Acknowledgements</title>
    <p>
      We would like to thank the rstats community for sharing and documenting code, Maria Boylan for pushing an initial blog idea into this book, and Linh Lazarus for editing an earlier version of the project.
    </p>
  </appendix>

  <appendix xml:id="back-authors">
    <title>Authors</title>

    <section xml:id="author-ekarin">
      <title>Ekarin E. Pongpipat, Ph.D.</title>
      <p>
        Ekarin E. Pongpipat is a postdoctoral scientist at The University of Texas at Dallas examining how neural systems change with age. He earned his PhD in Cognition and Neuroscience at The University of Texas at Dallas and has more than five years of teaching and tutoring experience in statistics.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section xml:id="author-giuseppe">
      <title>Giuseppe G. Miranda, Ph.D.</title>
      <p>
        Giuseppe G. Miranda earned his PhD in Cognition and Neuroscience at The University of Texas at Dallas. His interests include brain structure, aging, dopamine, executive function, intervention research, data analysis, and statistics.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section xml:id="author-matthew">
      <title>Matthew J. Kmiecik, Ph.D.</title>
      <p>
        Matthew J. Kmiecik is a postdoctoral research fellow at NorthShore University HealthSystem studying neural mechanisms underlying multimodal hypersensitivity in chronic pain conditions. He earned his PhD in Cognition and Neuroscience from The University of Texas at Dallas.
      </p>
    </section>
  </appendix>

